6
00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Well, the relationship between humans, honey and the bees which make it goes back thousands of years

7
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:32.000
Priced for its taste and medicinal properties in ancient times honey was known as liquid gold

8
00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:35.000
But now thanks to modern farming methods

9
00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:40.000
Population of many insects including bees are in decline

10
00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:48.000
Sersha, a worried listener from London called BBC World Service Programm crowd science about the problem

11
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:53.000
I'm Sersha from UK and my question is, can honey help save bees?

12
00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:58.000
I've been vegan for about nine years and I don't eat honey myself

13
00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:05.000
But I still have a question mark around it because I know there are bee populations of declining

14
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:10.000
Sersha is a vegan, someone who doesn't eat anything which comes from animals

15
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:15.000
Not just meat but things like milk, eggs and honey too

16
00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:22.000
Although Sersha doesn't eat honey herself, she says there's a question mark around eating honey

17
00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:28.000
The phrase a question mark around something means there's doubt or uncertainty about something

18
00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:34.000
And what Sersha is uncertain about is whether eating honey might actually save bees

19
00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:41.000
So, would it be better for declining bee populations if more people ate honey?

